text: Hey
still mad yes what you did was
unforgivable hi everyone
Anthony Fantino here internet's busiest
music nerd it's time for a review billy
woods history will absolve me billy
woods is an elusive DC MC and according
to his label backwoods studios this is
his second official full-length solo
album and his first in 8 years of course
between the releases of these two albums
he spent a good deal of his career being
one half of these super cron flight
brothers but now he is back at sort of a
lone wolf capacity with this album and i
would say a lot about what Billy woods
does has progressed since his last LP
the chalice pretty much everything from
the recording to the beats to billy's
personality and flow it's it's really an
improvement on all fronts
now even though this album does have
great great production ultimately it's
Billy what attracts me to this LP he's
got this really tough as nails persona
but it does not feel like pointless
posturing throughout the album which I
really hate but he doesn't really spend
all that much time bragging anyway where
I get all this toughness from it's just
the really gruff and raw vocal delivery
that he has in his rhymes he's just
really attention-grabbing to me as soon
as I heard him I just figured man a guy
this angry and emotive has got to have
something important to say
something interesting to say and
thankfully that is the case between the
20 tracks on this album there are some
songs on here that are kind of loose in
terms of subject matter just kind of all
over the place
throwing out lots of just sharp
criticisms lots of punchlines and plays
on words
and these days when a lot of MCS try to
embark upon that kind of thing I end up
kind of tuning out the MC and just
vibing with the B but I don't really
feel that way with Billy woods because
even when he is all over the place
lyrically he's still dropping gems like
the opening line on the track crocodile
tears which is clearly aimed at other
rappers 32 bars and how you rob and kill
your neighbors and still have the nerve
to ask God to save you and the problem
with the army is they want to be the
boss the problem with secret police is
they're like a dirty gun you can't toss
so yeah there is some really great smart
free-range lyricism on this album that
that ranges from being pretty hot to
good but for me Billy is at his most
potent when he has a subject matter he's
focusing on and there are a lot of odd
about tracks on here doing that like the
track cash for gold which miracle II
paints a portrait of strip clubs strip
club life these women who are kind of
subjecting themselves peddling their
bodies for just chunk change and then
kind of talking about the guys who go to
these places and depicting them as just
being soulless apes with no compassion
who are kind of there to just pretend
they're rich and make it rain and and
put their child support money into
g-strings or the track Bill Cosby which
is about this father who shouldn't have
even really been a father in the first
place and wished he never had kids or
gotten in this relationship and now he's
just growing to be this bitter freakin
jerk the track DMCA is really sharp
criticism of the music industry and
music fans and the Internet age kind of
just downloading uploading and then
deleting from their computers every
piece of music that they listen to kind
of this really disgusting purge cycle
the track Pompilius is really intense
track talking about just war crimes and
military violence and injustice now
billy has this flow where he doesn't
really ride the groove
the track he's on too hard but he is on
tempo the Rhymes and his verses just
kind of come together like part rapping
part ranting making him sort of a
combination of an emcee and just an
all-out madman in a way he kind of
reminds me of MF DOOM and that he has
really dark and gritty personality with
a very very consistent flow but Billy
woods also kind of reminds me of guys
like del the funky homosapien where he's
very up and in-your-face making these
just unapologetic tell-it-like-it-is
observations left and right and he's got
this really kind of forceful delivery
and this affinity for very unorthodox
instrumentals that also reminds me of
guys like LP or projects like cannibal
ox to me the guests on this album can be
kind of hit or miss some of them just
indulging in the kind of posturing that
Billy does not do hence why I like him
now the production on this thing to me
is just stellar but Billy has a history
of rapping over
unconventional stuff on his last album
he rapped over a Velvet Underground
sample of all things and I'd say he's
even getting more adventurous this time
around with guys like Willie Green am
breakups Marmaduke NASA and man mantas
on the beats the opening track is really
kind of dark and murky and gives the
feeling of Billy woods kind of crawling
very slowly out of this swamp to return
to hip-hop again in a solo capacity and
the track crocodile years is the
ass-kicking face-punching
track that this album needed to really
get things started
I love the skipping guitar leads on the
tractor we sharp synthesizers the track
body of work has this really slow
lumbering tempo that goes along with the
vocal sample really well the vocal
sample is this woman's voice singing
about breaking rocks in a chain gang and
just the tambourine on the track
resembles that of a chain rat
in just the heaviness of the bee just
feels like you're slaving away breaking
rocks
I love the mournful strings on the
opener the really quirky piano on the
track Bill Cosby adds to the comedy of
that track in a big way and the track
headband is just one gigantic Led
Zeppelin sample there's not a beat on
this thing that I didn't think was at
least good
the only spot on this album
instrumentally that I didn't care for as
much was the track pump up the volume
where the singer Lorenz is featured on
the track and her voice just kind of
flies out of nowhere against another
sample and that kind of feels like it's
just thrown on to the beat in a really
sloppy way though that seems to have
been done purposely I still don't really
love it outside of that there's not
really much I could say that's bad about
this album I do think it tends to drag
on a little too long maybe a leaner
album would have hit me with with more
force but there are so many great lyrics
on here and fantastic instrumentals that
re listening and relisting and re
listening can be extremely rewarding
kind of feeling a late decent 8 on this
thing what do you guys think of it did
you love it did you hate it why and what
should I review next anthony Fantan Oh
Billy woods forever
